Incident.Summary: -Single vehicle accident, overturned vehicle. -Driver was a juvenile and stated that he had alcohol that night. Driver was placed through SFST. -Driver was arrested for DUI/DWI. 23-031. -While searching his person, marijuana under 1.5 oz was recovered from his right pocket.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
MARYLAND STATE POLICE BEL AIR BARRACK "D"
HARFORD COUNTY, MARYLAND
This incident was recorded. Marked Unit D-10's in-car camera and Tpr. Rowe's body worn camera were working properly.

OFFENDER
Case # 23-MSP-003641
Defendant: Joseph Dean Bazzetta
Date of Birth: 09/09/2005
Date of Arrest: 01/29/2023
Time of Arrest: 0418 hours
DUI #: 23-031
DUI Citation #: 16100XD3

FIRST DUI OFFENSE

CERTIFICATES AND TRAINING:

*I am trained to administer Standardized Field Sobriety Tests through the Maryland State Police and
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.

*I am trained and certified to conduct preliminary breathalyzer tests by the Maryland State Police.

*I received Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement(ARIDE) training through the Maryland State Police in April 2022.

Phase #1 - Vehicle in Motion

    On January 29, 2023, at approximately 0355 hours, I, Trooper Rowe (#7015), currently assigned to the Maryland State Police Bel Air Barrack, responded to a single vehicle collision at northbound Conowingo Road at Hickory Bypass, Bel Air, Maryland. Investigation revealed the vehicle ran straight through a grassy median from the right turn lane, traveled across all lanes of Conowingo Road, and struck the curb on the other side causing the vehicle to overturn and land on its roof. The vehicle was identified as a silver Nissan Sentra displaying Maryland registration “4EB6494”.

Phase #2 - Personal Contact

Upon making contact with the driver of the vehicle, I detected the odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from the driver's breath and/or person. The driver's eyes were bloodshot and glassy. The driver advised me that he and his friend were coming from a friend's house. The driver was identified by his Maryland Driver's License as Joseph Dean Bazzetta (2/M DOB: 09/09/2005). I asked Bazzetta how much alcohol he had that night. Bazzetta advised me that he had one to one and a half beers earlier. I requested that Bazzetta submit to Standardized Field Sobriety Tests, which he agreed to take.

Phase #3 - Pre-Arrest Screening

The tests were conducted on the right lane of southbound Conowingo Road at Hickory Bypass, Bel Air, Maryland. The surface was dry, level, and free from obvious debris. Bazzetta displayed no visible injuries. The front facing emergency lights of all patrol vehicles were deactivated during all phases of testing.

I asked Bazzetta the following questions:

Daily/Regular Medications - NONE.
Glasses - NONE.
Contacts - NONE.
Injuries - NONE.

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS TEST (6/6 clues displayed)

I used my pen as a stimulus and held it approximately 12 to 15 inches from Bazzetta's eyes. His eyes displayed no resting nystagmus and his pupils were equal in size. His eyes also showed equal tracking. He was advised to stand with his feet together and his hands down at his sides during the instruction, demonstration, and throughout the test. I asked Bazzetta if he could see the tip of my stimulus, and he stated that he could. I observed his eyes to be bloodshot and glassy. Bazzetta was instructed to follow the stimulus with his eyes only, keeping his head still. After stating that he understood the instructions, Bazzetta attempted the test with the following results:

1. Lack of Smooth Pursuit - Present in both eyes.
2. Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation - Present in both eyes.
3. Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 degrees - Present in both eyes.
4. Vertical Gaze Nystagmus - Present in both eyes.

WALK AND TURN (6/8 clues displayed)

Bazzetta was placed on the straight line of the right shoulder of the road way. Bazzetta was asked if he was comfortable to walk and balance in his shoes. He stated he was. Bazzetta was instructed to stand on that straight line with his left foot and then place his right foot in front of his left foot with the right heel touching the toe of his left foot. Bazzetta was instructed to stand in this manner while standing straight with his hands to his sides. Bazzetta was then further instructed to remain in that position while the test instructions were given, the test was demonstrated, and throughout the test, which Bazzetta stated he understood. Bazzetta was instructed to take nine heel-to-toe steps along the straight line in front of him. Bazzetta was told after the ninth step, he was to turn around by keeping his front foot planted on the ground, and he would take a small series of steps with his other foot to turn around. After turning around, he was to take an additional nine heel-to-toe steps back along the same straight line he had come from. I then demonstrated the test for Bazzetta, taking only three steps instead of taking nine on each pass, reminding him that he will be taking nine steps. Bazzetta was then instructed to watch his feet at all times while walking, to count out his steps out loud, to keep his arms down at his sides during the test, and to not stop walking until the test was completed. I asked Bazzetta if he understood the instructions, and he stated that he did. I then asked Bazzetta to begin the test with the following results:

Instructional Stage

-Nothing observed

Walking Stage (1st Nine Steps)

-Missed heel to toe by more than 1/2 inch on steps 6, 7, and 8.
-Stepped off the line by 1/2 inch on step 6.
-Stopped walking briefly after step 6.
-Raised arms throughout the test.
-Completed 19 steps when instructed to complete 9.

The Turn

-Completed improperly, Bazzetta lifted his other foot that was supposed to remain planted.

Walking Stage (2nd Nine Steps)

-Raised his arms throughout the test
-Missed heel to toe by more than 1/2 inch on steps 1, 2, 3, and 4.
-Completed 17 steps when instructed to complete 9.

ONE LEG STAND (4/4 clues displayed)

Bazzetta was instructed to stand with his feet together and his hands flat to his sides while the test instructions and demonstration were given. When instructed to start, he was to raise the foot of his choice off the ground in front of him approximately 6 inches, keeping his legs straight and his toes pointed out in front of him, parallel to the ground. While his leg was raised, he was to count out loud by starting at one thousand (one thousand one, one thousand two, one thousand three...) and to continue counting until told to stop. After demonstrating the test, Bazzetta advised he understood, stating that he would be raising his left foot off the ground.

Instructional Stage:

-Nothing observed.

Balancing and Counting Stage

-Swayed left to right for the entire test.
-Put his foot down briefly at 16 seconds.
-Hopped on one leg at 14 seconds.
-Raised arms from 1 second to 14 seconds.

While on roadside, I had Bazzetta open his mouth to check for any foreign material that would interfere in taking a breath tests, nothing was observed. I asked Bazzetta if he would submit to a Preliminary Breath Test on roadside, which he refused to take. Bazzetta was placed under arrest for DUI/DWI at approximately 0418 hours. I again asked Bazzetta how much alcohol he had that night and this time he stated he had three to four beers and one shot. A search incident to arrest was conducted on Bazzetta's person, marijuana in the amount of personal use was located in his right pocket. The marijuana was seized at approximately 0420 hours. I know the substance was marijuana due to my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper. I then placed him in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle.

OBSERVATIONS:

-Causing a single vehicle accident.
-Glassy and Bloodshot eyes.
-Odor of an alcoholic beverage.
-Admitting to consuming alcoholic beverages earlier that night.
-HGN: 6/6 clues displayed.
-Walk and Turn: 6/8 clues.
-One Leg Stand: 4/4 clues.

20 Minute Observation Period

While at the Maryland State Police Bel Air Barrack "D", Bazzetta was given a copy of the DR-15 Advice of Rights, so he could follow along as the DR-15 Advice of Rights was read out loud. Due to Bazzetta being a juvenile he was able to talk with his father before making his decision. Bazzetta signed the DR-15 at approximately 0457 hours acknowledging his consent to take the test. Sergeant Dudek(#5037), a certified Intoximeter Technician of the Maryland State Police, conducted the test for Bazzetta. Bazzetta's breath specimen was found to contain an alcohol concentration of 0.15 grams of alcohol per 210 liters of breath. Bazzetta was issued all pertinent documentations regarding the incident. Bazzetta was also issued a civil citation(3Z46639603) for possession of marijuana in the amount of personal use. Bazzetta was then released to his sober father, Stephen Bazzetta (2/M DOB: 05/01/1970), at approximately 0626 hours. The marijuana was then packaged properly per policy on Property Held P-334603.
Bazzetta was polite and cooperative during the entire incident.

All events occurred in Harford County, Maryland.

I request this case to be closed by arrest.

IncidentProperty.Description: One clear plastic baggie containing marijuana.
